{
  "answer": "For Allama Iqbal, *taqlīd* (طَقْلِيدْ, appearing as \"taqleed\" in transliteration) represents **blind imitation** or mechanical adherence, particularly in religious or spiritual practice—a habit he portrays as spiritually deadening and inferior even to self-destruction (*khudkushī*). In his poetry, he urges transcending it to pursue an authentic, self-forged path (*rasta*), rejecting reliance on external authorities like the legendary guide Khizr.[^1]\n\nIqbal further declares the era of *taqlīd* over (*gaya hai taqleed ka zamana*), supplanted by an age where truth (*ḥaqīqat*) manifests directly, rendering imitation (*majāz*) obsolete and mere talk unnecessary.[^2]\n\nThese poetic critiques align with Iqbal's broader philosophy of dynamic selfhood (*khudī*) over static conformity, though his prose works (e.g., *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam*) critiquing *taqlīd* in Islamic jurisprudence are not in this corpus.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 9 (\"Majnoon ne sheher chhora to sehra bhi chhor de\"), [p-e3d084](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/09-majnoon-ne-sheher-chhora-to-sehra-bhi-chhor-de/translation/#p-e3d084).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 6 (\"Zamana dekhe ga jab mere dil se mahshar uthe ga guftugu ka\"), [p-4b6816](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/06-zamana-dekhe-ga-jab-mere-dil-se-mahshar-uthe-ga-gu/translation/#p-4b6816).",
